b"[![](../../cdshop/cdinfo.jpg)](../../cdshop/index.htm)  \n[Sacred Texts](../../index.htm)  [Hinduism](../index.htm)  [Index](index.htm)\n[Previous](sbe30015.htm)  [Next](sbe30017.htm)\n\n* * *\n\n[Buy this Book at\nAmazon.com](http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0543983862/internetsacredte)\n\n* * *\n\n_The Grihya Sutras, Part 2 (SBE30)_ , by Hermann Oldenberg, [1892], at sacred-\ntexts.com\n\n* * *\n\n### K\xc3\x82 _N_ _D_ IK\xc3\x82 4. 4\n\n1\\. When she mounts the chariot, let him murmur the verse, 'Adorned with Ki\n_m_ _s_ uka flowers, of _S_ almali wood' (MB. I, 3, 11).\n\n2. 2 On the way he should address crossways, rivers and unevennesses (of the soil), big trees, and burial grounds, with (the verse), 'May no waylayers meet us' (ibid. 12).\n\n3. 3 If the axle breaks, or something that is bound gets loose, or if the chariot is overturned, or if some other accident happens, they should put wood on the fire which they carry with themselves, should\n\np. 50\n\nmake oblations (of \xc3\x82 _g_ ya) with the Vyah _ri_ tis, should procure a new\npiece (instead of that which has been damaged), and should besmear it with the\nremnants of the \xc3\x82 _g_ ya (that has been offered), with (the verse), 'He who\nwithout binding' (Sama-veda I, 244).\n\n4\\. Having sung the Vamadevya, he should mount (again).\n\n5\\. When they have arrived, the Vamadevya (is sung).\n\n6\\. When (the bride) has reached the house, Brahma _n_ a women of good\ncharacter, whose husbands and sons are living, make her descend (from the\nchariot), and make her sit down on a bull's hide with (the verse which the\nhusband recites), 'Here, ye cows, bring forth calves' (MB. I, 3, 13).\n\n7\\. They should place a boy in her lap.\n\n8. 8 Into the joined hands of that (boy) they should throw lotus-roots (?),\n\n9\\. Or fruits.\n\n10. 10 After she has made that boy rise, she sacrifices the eight 'firm' \xc3\x82 _g_ ya oblations with (the formula), 'Here is steadiness' (MB. I, 3, 14).\n\n11\\. When she has finished, she puts a piece of wood (on the fire) and\nrespectfully salutes the Gurus, according to seniority, with their Gotra\nnames. Then they may do what they like.\n\n* * *\n\n### Footnotes\n\n[49:4](sbe30016.htm#fr_212) The way of the bridegroom with the bride to their\nnew home, and their arrival.\n\n[49:2](sbe30016.htm#fr_213) Perhaps a part of this Sutra is based on a half\nSloka, the two parts of which have been transposed in the prose version, mahav\n_ri_ kshan _s_ ma _s_ ana _m_ _k_ a nadi _s_ _k_ a vishama _n_ i _k_ a.\n\n[49:3](sbe30016.htm#fr_214) Comp. Paraskara I, 10.\n\n[50:8](sbe30016.htm#fr_215) The explanation of _s_ akalo _t_ a as _s_ aluka is\ndoubtful. Prof. Weber believes that we ought to read _s_ akalosh _t_ an (lumps\nof dung); see Indische Studien, V, 371.\n\n[50:10](sbe30016.htm#fr_216) 'Firm' oblations seem to mean oblations by which\nthe wife obtains a firm abode in her husband's house. Comp. Indische Studien,\nV, 376.\n\n* * *\n\n[Next: II, 5](sbe30017.htm)\n\n"